27:12.779 --> 27:14.414
about the English language.

27:14.447 --> 27:15.949
They expect
the rest of the world

27:15.982 --> 27:18.318
not only to learn it,

27:18.351 --> 27:20.521
but to speak it
the way they do.

27:20.554 --> 27:23.323
Tang Jingyu doesn't speak
English very well.

27:25.859 --> 27:28.428
He even sounds a little funny.

27:28.461 --> 27:29.863
Combine his accent

27:29.896 --> 27:32.265
with the fact that he got blown
off a toilet.

27:34.400 --> 27:35.468
I laughed.

27:36.837 --> 27:38.338
Maybe some of you did, as well.

27:39.973 --> 27:42.008
But what's not so damn funny

27:43.109 --> 27:45.145
is that this man was hurt.

27:45.178 --> 27:47.681
He suffered third-degree burns.

27:47.714 --> 27:50.617
He is scarred for life.

27:50.651 --> 27:51.818
Is he partly to blame?

27:51.852 --> 27:54.521
Absolutely, he should not
have been smoking.

27:54.555 --> 27:55.856
But the question is

27:55.889 --> 27:58.525
"Who is to blame more?"

27:58.559 --> 28:01.535
Is it foreseeable
that people smoke in lavatories?

28:01.568 --> 28:02.468
Of course it is.

28:02.503 --> 28:04.170
People smoke in bathrooms

28:04.204 --> 28:06.006
in high schools,

28:06.039 --> 28:07.207
on airplanes,

28:07.240 --> 28:10.210
in gas stations.

28:10.243 --> 28:12.746
And knowing
that this sometimes goes on,

28:12.779 --> 28:15.949
you do not put flammables

28:15.982 --> 28:17.584
in a toilet bowl.

28:19.520 --> 28:20.587
To do so,

28:20.621 --> 28:23.023
that is negligence.

28:24.257 --> 28:26.660
And as amusing as it all may be,

28:26.693 --> 28:29.495
as a result of this negligence,

28:30.964 --> 28:33.767
an innocent man was injured.

28:33.800 --> 28:35.836
He waited five years
to get to trial,

28:37.771 --> 28:39.673
only to be laughed at
by his own lawyer.

28:43.309 --> 28:44.845
This man suffered real pain,

28:48.381 --> 28:49.750
and he deserves better.

29:04.237 --> 29:06.840
He knew the room
had just been painted.

29:06.873 --> 29:09.710
He was told not to go in.

29:09.743 --> 29:12.312
The "No smoking" signs
were posted.

29:12.345 --> 29:14.981
The room had fumes and still,

29:16.149 --> 29:18.384
he lights a match.

29:19.520 --> 29:21.054
He caused this.

29:21.087 --> 29:23.890
He blew up my client's bathroom

29:23.924 --> 29:26.292
and he's suing.

29:26.326 --> 29:27.493
Come on.

29:27.528 --> 29:29.630
That may not technically
be a legal argument

29:29.663 --> 29:31.331
but let me say it again,

29:31.364 --> 29:34.000
this was his negligence,
not ours,

29:35.301 --> 29:36.703
and you know that.

29:45.311 --> 29:47.948
The question
is a simple one really,

29:50.016 --> 29:51.384
is it foreseeable

29:51.417 --> 29:53.887
that someone might light a match

29:53.920 --> 29:56.456
and drop it in a toilet bowl?

29:57.423 --> 30:00.133
If no, find for the defendant.

30:00.166 --> 30:02.368
If yes, find for the plaintiff.

30:12.779 --> 30:14.147
(elevator bell dings)

30:23.790 --> 30:25.826
I don't know
whether you saved yourself,

30:28.995 --> 30:30.897
but that was a good closing,
Tara.

30:30.931 --> 30:32.966
It was simple and persuasive.

30:34.034 --> 30:35.569
You did a very good job.

30:38.271 --> 30:39.239
Thank you.

30:45.846 --> 30:47.047
Can we talk?

30:51.384 --> 30:54.287
You heard Andrea Mills'
testimony.

30:54.320 --> 30:56.857
There was a dispute over price.

30:56.890 --> 30:58.859
The defendant pulled his gun

31:00.093 --> 31:01.535
and he fired.

31:01.568 --> 31:04.437
You can't claim self-defense,
ladies and gentlemen,

31:04.470 --> 31:06.306
if you cause somebody

31:06.339 --> 31:07.908
to reach for a gun

31:07.941 --> 31:10.210
only so you can then blast him,

31:10.243 --> 31:12.713
that's ridiculous.

31:12.746 --> 31:14.414
Now, to be honest,

31:14.447 --> 31:16.950
I don't know what the hell
defense counsel is up to

31:16.983 --> 31:18.151
in this trial.

31:18.184 --> 31:20.521
I suspect all that nonsense
was motivated

31:20.554 --> 31:22.122
by the fact that Mr. Shore

31:22.155 --> 31:23.757
knew he had no case.

31:23.790 --> 31:26.760
The defendant pulled a gun

31:26.793 --> 31:28.128
in front of an eyewitness

31:28.161 --> 31:29.696
and shot somebody.

31:29.730 --> 31:30.997
What could his lawyer

31:31.031 --> 31:32.899
really say or do?

31:32.933 --> 31:35.268
So Mr. Shore tried
to deflect attention

31:35.301 --> 31:36.870
onto himself,

31:36.903 --> 31:39.706
but this isn't about
a lawyer's antics.

31:39.740 --> 31:41.708
We're not in this room

31:41.742 --> 31:44.210
to enjoy defense
counsel's sideshow.

31:44.244 --> 31:46.913
We are here
because his client

31:46.947 --> 31:48.649
committed a murder.

31:48.682 --> 31:50.183
A man is dead.

32:04.270 --> 32:05.772
At the beginning,

32:05.806 --> 32:07.040
you heard me mention

32:07.073 --> 32:09.142
that I was assigned this case.

32:09.175 --> 32:11.311
We have this pro bono program

32:11.344 --> 32:14.280
because somebody has to be here
for the guy.

32:14.314 --> 32:16.349
See, that's where
our judicial system

32:16.382 --> 32:17.651
actually exceeds real life.

32:17.684 --> 32:18.885
In here,

32:18.919 --> 32:20.921
somebody's got
to be there for the guy.

32:20.954 --> 32:22.956
In life,

32:22.989 --> 32:25.425
Marshall Bagnelle
never met his father.

32:25.458 --> 32:26.893
His mother worked full-time,

32:26.927 --> 32:28.795
leaving him home alone all day.

32:28.829 --> 32:31.397
He got involved early in drugs.

32:31.431 --> 32:32.432
There was nobody there

32:32.465 --> 32:33.767
to get him in treatment.

32:33.800 --> 32:35.902
His parents, his teachers,

32:35.936 --> 32:38.138
school principals,
probation officers,

32:38.171 --> 32:40.340
people vested
with the responsibility

32:40.373 --> 32:42.142
of caring for him a little,

32:42.175 --> 32:44.545
they didn't.

32:44.578 --> 32:46.580
And he became a drug addict.

32:46.613 --> 32:47.914
Now, I'm not gonna stand here

32:47.948 --> 32:49.082
and ask you to care for him.

32:49.115 --> 32:50.283
God forbid.

32:50.316 --> 32:52.152
But what I will ask

32:52.185 --> 32:53.720
is for you to recognize

32:53.754 --> 32:55.522
that life hasn't been very fair

32:55.556 --> 32:56.957
to Marshall Bagnelle.

32:56.990 --> 32:58.324
The irony is,

32:58.358 --> 33:00.166
by pulling that trigger
three times,

33:00.200 --> 33:02.235
he gets thrown into a system

33:02.268 --> 33:05.038
that's required
to treat him fairly.

33:05.071 --> 33:06.406
He gets a right

33:06.439 --> 33:08.208
to a fair trial,

33:08.241 --> 33:11.211
and if you afford him
that right,

33:11.244 --> 33:13.379
he must necessarily

33:13.413 --> 33:15.215
be found not guilty.

33:16.683 --> 33:18.218
The supposed eyewitness

33:18.251 --> 33:20.386
admitted she was watching
television,

33:20.420 --> 33:21.287
her own words.

33:21.321 --> 33:22.956
She wasn't looking

33:22.989 --> 33:23.790
at the men

33:23.824 --> 33:24.558
at the time

33:24.591 --> 33:26.459
my client drew his weapon.

33:26.492 --> 33:27.761
She told you that.

33:27.794 --> 33:30.697
She did not see.

33:30.731 --> 33:32.265
Now, what she did see

33:32.298 --> 33:34.000
supports precisely

33:34.034 --> 33:35.769
what Marshall told you.

33:35.802 --> 33:38.605
The victim was going
for his gun.

33:38.639 --> 33:39.706
At that point,

33:39.740 --> 33:42.142
my client could only shoot

33:42.175 --> 33:43.644
or be shot,

33:43.677 --> 33:45.612
that's self-defense.

33:45.646 --> 33:48.582
That's classic self-defense.

33:48.615 --> 33:50.116
And think about it,

33:50.150 --> 33:53.086
if Marshall Bagnelle
wasn't acting in self-defense,

33:53.119 --> 33:55.956
why did he not shoot
Andrea Mills?

33:56.657 --> 33:58.224
Why did he leave behind

33:58.258 --> 33:59.960
this eyewitness?

33:59.993 --> 34:01.334
Perhaps because

34:01.367 --> 34:03.403
she wasn't about

34:03.436 --> 34:05.005
to shoot him.

34:06.372 --> 34:08.574
Of course, you could choose
to ignore all this,

34:08.609 --> 34:10.010
simply because you don't care,

34:10.043 --> 34:11.645
not only about
Marshall Bagnelle,

34:11.678 --> 34:13.079
but also about the law

34:13.112 --> 34:15.014
you swore to uphold,

34:15.047 --> 34:18.018
swore to because what we do
pretend to care about

34:18.051 --> 34:21.021
is the integrity of this system.

34:21.054 --> 34:23.456
We do believe
in that cherished notion

34:23.489 --> 34:24.725
of the fair trial.

34:24.757 --> 34:26.527
We're fiercely loyal

34:26.560 --> 34:28.829
to the ideal that a prosecution

34:28.862 --> 34:30.697
must satisfy
its burden of proof.

34:30.731 --> 34:32.232
They haven't done that here.

34:34.199 --> 34:35.969
As dearly as we'd all love

34:36.002 --> 34:37.638
to send Mr. Bagnelle to prison,

34:37.670 --> 34:39.606
we cannot know for a fact

34:39.639 --> 34:40.674
that the victim,

34:40.706 --> 34:41.775
a drug dealer,

34:41.808 --> 34:44.043
rumored to have killed
somebody before,

34:44.077 --> 34:45.712
didn't draw his gun

34:45.746 --> 34:47.313
to shoot first.

34:47.347 --> 34:48.782
We cannot know

34:48.815 --> 34:50.583
beyond all reasonable doubt

34:50.617 --> 34:52.085
that Marshall Bagnelle

34:52.118 --> 34:54.888
didn't fear for his life.

34:57.658 --> 35:00.333
And if he did reasonably

35:00.366 --> 35:02.202
fear for his life.

35:03.403 --> 35:05.672
If you believe it's possible

35:06.873 --> 35:09.510
that he feared for his life

35:11.578 --> 35:13.647
you must find him not guilty.

35:17.751 --> 35:19.052
Unless, of course,

35:21.922 --> 35:23.456
you don't care.

35:45.912 --> 35:47.914
Sixty-three thousand?

35:47.948 --> 35:49.415
We could get more

35:49.449 --> 35:51.818
but we could get nothing.

35:51.852 --> 35:53.253
I think it's a decent offer.

35:53.286 --> 35:54.788
Clearly, you were hurt

35:54.821 --> 35:56.122
but just as clearly

35:56.156 --> 35:58.224
there was contributory
negligence.

36:00.300 --> 36:02.202
What think?

36:02.235 --> 36:03.403
I think we should take it.

36:05.539 --> 36:06.306
What think?

36:08.775 --> 36:10.744
I believe that we should accept,

36:10.777 --> 36:11.612
as well.

36:14.781 --> 36:16.617
Okay.

36:16.650 --> 36:18.018
FRUTT: Okay.

36:18.051 --> 36:19.419
I'm going to accept, then.

36:21.187 --> 36:22.889
Okay.

36:22.923 --> 36:25.425
FRUTT: This is a good result,
Mr. Tang.

36:27.027 --> 36:27.994
Okay.

36:38.772 --> 36:41.675
Thank you for closing.

36:44.745 --> 36:47.247
Good closing.

36:47.280 --> 36:50.216
(music playing)

36:51.417 --> 36:52.653
Mr. Tang,

36:54.688 --> 36:56.523
I owe you a sincere...

36:57.791 --> 36:59.259
apology.

36:59.292 --> 37:00.060
Give already.

37:00.093 --> 37:02.235
Thank you.

37:02.268 --> 37:04.838
Appreciate closing.

37:12.746 --> 37:14.714
People laugh at me always.

37:16.015 --> 37:18.184
One reason I angry.

37:20.721 --> 37:23.524
Apologize for anger.

37:25.091 --> 37:27.293
You don't need to apologize
for anything.

37:32.398 --> 37:35.101
Not male puppet.

37:41.107 --> 37:42.042
Thank you.

37:50.083 --> 37:51.852
TAMARA: How long
do they usually take?

37:54.154 --> 37:55.455
SHORE: There's really
no telling.

37:55.488 --> 37:58.224
The judge will probably
keep us here until 6:00.

38:01.735 --> 38:03.269
Look, I'm sorry
I jumped you.

38:04.805 --> 38:07.307
I see now you, uh,

38:07.340 --> 38:09.643
kind of had a strategy.

38:09.676 --> 38:11.612
Why didn't you just tell us
what it was?

38:12.746 --> 38:14.280
Takes the fun out of it.

38:17.350 --> 38:19.786
I suppose I should thank you
and all.

38:19.820 --> 38:21.321
Well, I'd prefer money.

38:24.024 --> 38:25.592
You're a big fraud,
you know that?

38:27.227 --> 38:28.895
You do care about my son.

38:30.564 --> 38:31.732
You're not fooling me.

38:37.671 --> 38:38.805
Jury's back.

38:40.206 --> 38:43.143
(music playing)

39:03.036 --> 39:05.271
What does it mean
that it's so fast?

39:05.305 --> 39:07.307
It's usually a good sign
when you win,

39:07.340 --> 39:08.875
but a bad one when you lose.

39:12.178 --> 39:13.647
We'll know in a second,
Marshall.

39:13.680 --> 39:14.881
Hang in there.

39:23.757 --> 39:24.991
Members of the jury,

39:25.025 --> 39:27.293
have you reached a verdict?

39:27.327 --> 39:28.695
We have, Your Honor.

39:28.729 --> 39:30.230
ROBBINS: The defendant
will please rise.

39:33.499 --> 39:34.735
What say you?

39:34.768 --> 39:36.503
In the matter
of the Commonwealth

39:36.537 --> 39:38.271
vs. Marshall Bagnelle,

39:38.304 --> 39:41.041
on the charge of murder
in the first degree,

39:41.074 --> 39:42.408
we find the defendant,

39:42.442 --> 39:43.977
Marshall Bagnelle,

39:44.010 --> 39:45.378
not guilty.

39:47.213 --> 39:48.515
In the matter
of the Commonwealth

39:48.549 --> 39:50.116
vs. Marshall Bagnelle,

39:50.150 --> 39:52.819
on the charge of murder
in the second degree,

39:52.853 --> 39:53.987
we find the defendant,

39:54.020 --> 39:55.488
Marshall Bagnelle,

39:57.791 --> 40:00.333
guilty.

40:00.366 --> 40:01.902
ROBBINS: Ladies and gentlemen
of the jury,

40:01.935 --> 40:02.969
you are dismissed

40:03.003 --> 40:05.305
with the thanks of this court.

40:05.338 --> 40:07.941
Security, take the defendant
into custody.

40:07.974 --> 40:09.342
We are adjourned.

40:09.375 --> 40:10.443
(gavel bangs)

40:13.146 --> 40:14.981
We'll explore grounds
for appeal, Marshall.

40:16.416 --> 40:18.685
Marshall, look at me.

40:18.719 --> 40:20.253
There's still some things
we can do.

40:20.286 --> 40:21.988
We'll explore all grounds
for appeal.

40:25.491 --> 40:27.493
Marshall,
I'll let you know, okay?

40:29.329 --> 40:31.464
Marshall,

40:31.497 --> 40:32.966
I'll come visit you tomorrow.

40:39.105 --> 40:42.042
(music playing)

40:59.459 --> 41:02.402
(music playing)

41:25.826 --> 41:26.793
WOMAN: You stinker!

41:26.927 --> 41:29.863
(music playing)
